  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">On pages one through two of this manuscript, there is a letter by Sarah Poole to Maria Weston Chapman. Sarah Poole thanks Maria W. Chapman for her gifts, including &quot;your beautiful &apos;Report.&apos;&quot; She remarks on &quot;the stillness of death&quot; in her own land.&quot; Henry C. Wright has &quot;a sleepless time of it amongst us.&quot; She quotes from a letter by Henry C. Wright to Sarah Poole&apos;s brother, telling about Wright&apos;s engagements, sleeplessness, and his meetings with John Bright, etc. She comments about Henry C. Wright, &quot;our dear friend is much beloved by many in Ireland.&quot; Charles L. Remond&apos;s &quot;eloquent appeals&quot; aroused transient zeal, which quickly vanished.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">On pages two through four of this manuscript, there is a separate letter by Elizabeth Poole to Maria Weston Chapman. She has copied a poem by her friend Robert R. R. Moore, entitled &quot;On the Liberty Bell,&quot; and is submitting it for publication to the Liberty Bell.</subfield>
  </datafield>
